===Etymology===
{{af|en|Penn|sylvan|-ia|gloss1=William Penn|gloss2=woods|gloss3=land}}. 
On March 4, 1681, Charles II of England granted a land tract to {{w|lang=en|William Penn}} for the area that now includes Pennsylvania. Penn then founded a colony there as a place of religious freedom for Quakers, and named it for the {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|[[sylva]], [[silva]]|gloss=meaning "wood"}}, thus "Pennsylvania."

